00:56:03.730 --> 00:56:06.050
AUDIENCE: Mark, you
talked about the hostility

00:56:06.050 --> 00:56:10.120
that the London music
establishment had

00:56:10.120 --> 00:56:13.360
toward Liverpool, or
indifference, maybe.

00:56:13.360 --> 00:56:18.540
And yet there was in that
first batch of teen idols,

00:56:18.540 --> 00:56:21.540
there was one
Liverpudlian, Billy Fury.

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:25.310
But he didn't apparently
become sort of an icon

00:56:25.310 --> 00:56:30.987
for the other budding
musicians in Liverpool.

00:56:30.987 --> 00:56:32.570
Is there a particular
reason for that?

00:56:32.570 --> 00:56:34.861
MARK LEWISOHN: Yeah, Billy
Fury was the first Liverpool

00:56:34.861 --> 00:56:36.520
rock-and-roll star
before the Beatles.

00:56:36.520 --> 00:56:38.420
His real name was
Ronald Wycherly.

00:56:38.420 --> 00:56:42.390
And he actually was in the
same class at school as Ringo.

00:56:42.390 --> 00:56:45.760
But so embarrassing was
the Liverpool accent,

00:56:45.760 --> 00:56:47.970
or perceived to be in
those days in the UK--

00:56:47.970 --> 00:56:50.250
and that's another
thing the Beatles did.

00:56:50.250 --> 00:56:52.040
In my country, in
England, they completely

00:56:52.040 --> 00:56:53.630
changed the class system.

00:56:53.630 --> 00:56:55.770
Well, not changed it,
but challenged it.

00:56:55.770 --> 00:56:57.300
And opened it up to people.

00:56:57.300 --> 00:57:00.250
Because they had northern
working class accents.

00:57:00.250 --> 00:57:04.090
And that had always been
embarrassing before.

00:57:04.090 --> 00:57:07.270
Billy Fury never
said a word publicly

00:57:07.270 --> 00:57:08.730
because of his Liverpool accent.

00:57:08.730 --> 00:57:10.922
His manager said to
him, don't speak.

00:57:10.922 --> 00:57:12.880
And when he sang, he sang
in an American voice.

00:57:12.880 --> 00:57:14.713
So no one really knew
he was from Liverpool.

00:57:14.713 --> 00:57:15.620
It wasn't important.

00:57:15.620 --> 00:57:18.380
But when the Beatles broke
through, it's like, yeah,

00:57:18.380 --> 00:57:19.265
we're from Liverpool.

00:57:19.265 --> 00:57:20.140
We're from the north.

00:57:20.140 --> 00:57:22.170
You got a problem with that?

00:57:22.170 --> 00:57:24.590
And that was a real
challenge to people,

00:57:24.590 --> 00:57:27.010
which is why they received
hostility to begin with.

00:57:27.010 --> 00:57:29.200
But eventually,
within about a year,

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:33.090
everyone was putting on a
northern accent to be cool.

00:57:33.090 --> 00:57:38.150
That's just a small measure
of the impact that they had.

